@node "intro" "The trousers."
@toc "main"

    Why to reinvent the wheel? Well, our wheel doesn't gather any moss, unlike
    MSplit and chunker just to name a few. We here at the RRR's utilities
    division got so tired of waiting, and finally when we ran out of Pepsi,
    we got a vision from our Galactic masters, the purple toads, who instructed
    and gave us the technology to produce such a wonderful tool as Ms. Onyx is.

    Here you are. The ultimate split command replacement, Ms. Onyx. Not only she
    will cut the files into smaller blocks, but she will also cheer you up with
    her cute remarks. ;)

@endnode

@node "req" "The panties."
@toc "main"

    An Amiga with an 020 processor is required. Due to the heavy 32-bit calculations,
    we decided not to include a limited 000 version. All you 68000 owners can
    use the MJoin and chunker to your fine purposes.

    Also a nice chunk of memory is required due to the nature of our fast data
    splitting routines. The more you have, the bigger files you can cut into pieces.

    A last minutes addition makes it possible to chop very large files. If
    Ms. Onyx cannot allocate as much memory as the chopped file weigths, then
    a smaller buffer will be allocated and data will be loaded in in parts.
    The smaller buffer is as big as one of the outputted sections.

@endnode

@node "usage" "The socks."
@toc "main"

    > cut [FILENAME] [BASENAME] [SIZE] [ENTER]

    [FILENAME] - The file to split into smaller pieces.
    [BASENAME] - Name for the smaller files. Ms. Onyx will add a numerical
                 extension to every little block she gives out, so that her
                 companion, Ms. Sapphire, can join the blocks into a one major
                 file in correct order.
    [SIZE]     - The main file is divided into smaller files, which hold the
                 size you insert here.
    [ENTER]    - The button found on most keyboards. The c64 has a Return button.



    > cut RRR-CU10.LHA RRR-CU10 100 [ENTER]

   -> RRR-CU10.000     [100 bytes in size]
      RRR-CU10.001     [100 bytes in size]
      RRR-CU10.002...  [100 bytes in size]...


    When the program is running a panel will be shown.

          r[ū]       Left: 95%       w[ ]

    The r stands for reading data and w for writing data. From these buttons
    you can see what the program is doing. If it shows the read button more
    than once, then you can be sure that the slower cutting mode is enabled
    and a file larger than the computer's memory capasity is being cutted
    into pieces. May they rest in piece. ;)

    Left shows in percents the amount of work that is left.

    Note that you cannot stop Ms. Onyx while she's chopping the file.
    She's so keen on cutting that it would be dangerous to try to interrupt her. ;)

@endnode

@node "hist" "The cap."
@toc "main"

